16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-111 of Title 47, unless there
19 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 A. The Oklahoma Wrecker Services Division, a division of the
21 Department of Labor, is hereby created, which shall consist of such
22 divisions, sections, committees, offices and positions as may be
23 established by the Department of Labor or by law. The Division
24 shall employ a Division Director and a team of three employees to
Req. No. 16927 Page 3

1 inve stigate consumer complaints related to overcharging for
2 nonconsensual towing, recovery, storage fees, and violations of the
3 rules promulgated by the Oklahoma Wrecker and Towing Services Board.
4 Division employees shall act as analysts, administrative assistants,
5 administrative technicians, and investigators.
6 B. 1. The applicable powers, duties, and responsibilities
7 exercised by the Transportation Division of the Oklahoma Corporation
8 Commission relating to wrecker and towing services shall be fully
9 transferred to the Department of Labor on November 1, 2026. All
10 records, property, equipment, assets, monies, financial interests,
11 liabilities, matters pending, and funds of the Commission related to
12 wrecker and towing services shall be transferred to the Department
13 of Labor.
14 2. With the exception of initial inspections of wrecker and
15 towing facilities and equipment and rotation log requirements
16 performed by the Department of Public Safety, the applicable powers,
17 duties, and responsibilities for regulating the wrecker and towing
18 industry in this state exercised by the Department of Public Safety
19 shall be fully transferred to the Department of Labor on November 1,
20 2026. All records, property, equipment, assets, monies, financial
21 interests, liabilities, matters pending, and funds of the Department
22 of Public Safety related to wrecker and towing services shall be
23 transferred to the Department of Labor.
24
Req. No. 16927 Page 4

1 C. The Department of Labor shall succeed to any contractual
2 rights or responsibilities incurred by the Commission pertaining to
3 wrecker and towing services.
4 D. The administrative rules related to wrecker and towing
5 services previously promulgated by the Corporation Commission shall
6 be transferred to and become a part of the administrative rules of
7 the Department of Labor upon the effective date of this act. The
8 Office of Administrative Rules in the Office of the Secretary of
9 State shall provide adequate notice in "The Oklahoma Register" of
10 the transferred rules and shall place the transferred rules under
11 the Administrative Code section of the Department of Labor. On the
12 effective date of this act, any amendment, repeal, or addition to
13 the transferred rules shall be under the rulemaking authority of the
14 Department of Labor.
15 E. Aside from rules promulgated by the Department of Public
16 Safety pertaining to rotation logs and inspections of wrecker and
17 towing facilities and equipment, the administrative rules previously
18 promulgated by the Department of Public Safety shall be transferred
19 to and become a part of the administrative rules of the Department
20 of Labor upon the effective date of this act. The Office of
21 Administrative Rules in the Office of the Secretary of State shall
22 provide adequate notice in "The Oklahoma Register" of the
23 transferred rules and shall place the transferred rules under the
24 Administrative Code section of the Department of Labor. On the
Req. No. 16927 Page 5

1 effe ctive date of this act, any amendment, repeal, or addition to
2 the transferred rules shall be under the rulemaking authority of the
3 Department of Labor.
4 F. The Department of Labor, the Corporation Commission, and the
5 Department of Public Safety may enter into an agreement for the
6 transfer of personnel, if any, from the Commission and Department of
7 Public Safety to the Department of Labor. However, in no instance
8 shall more than four employees receive transfers. No employee shall
9 be transferred to the Department of Labor except on the freely given
10 written consent of the employee. Any employees who are transferred
11 to the Department of Labor shall not be required to accept a lesser
12 grade or salary than presently received. All employees shall retain
13 leave, sick, and annual time earned, and any retirement and
14 longevity benefits which have accrued during their tenure with the
15 Corporation Commission or the Department of Public Safety. The
16 transfer of any personnel between the state agencies shall be
17 coordinated with the Office of Management and Enterprise Services.
18 G. The Office of Management and Enterprise Services shall
19 coordinate the transfer of records, property, equipment, assets,
20 funds, allotments, purchase orders, liabilities, outstanding
21 financial obligations, or encumbrances provided for in this section.
22 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 951.1 of Title 47, unless there
24 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
Req. No. 16927 Page 6

1 A. There is hereby created, pursuant to the Oklahoma Sunset Law
2 until January 1, 2032, the Oklahoma Wrecker and Towing Services
3 Board which shall be the regulatory authority to the Oklahoma
4 Wrecker Services Division created in Section 1 of this act. The
5 Board shall be independent and shall consist of nine (9) members who
6 shall initially serve staggered terms of membership with the Board.
7 The initial staggered terms of membership of the Board shall be as
8 follows:
9 1. One member, who is in an industry unrelated to any other
10 member of the Board, appointed by the Governor from the state at
11 large whose membership shall expire June 30, 2028;
12 2. One member, who is in an industry unrelated to any other
13 member of the Board, appointed by Governor from the state at large
14 whose membership shall expire June 30, 2029;
15 3. One member holding a license or licensed by the Department
16 of Labor to engage in nonconsensual towing who operates in a county
17 with a population of one hundred thousand (100,000) or more,
18 according to the latest Federal Decennial Census, shall be appointed
19 by the President Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma State Senate and whose
20 membership shall expire June 30, 2030;
21 4. One member holding a license or licensed by the Department
22 of Labor to engage in nonconsensual towing who operates in a county
23 with a population of less than one hundred thousand (100,000),
24 according to the latest Federal Decennial Census, shall be appointed
Req. No. 16927 Page 7

1 by t he Speaker of the House of Representatives and whose membership
2 shall expire June 30, 2028;
3 5. One member from the Oklahoma Trucking Association shall be
4 appointed by the Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives
5 and whose membership shall expire June 30, 2029;
6 6. One member from law enforcement shall be appointed by the
7 Governor and whose membership shall expire June 30, 2030;
8 7. One member holding a license or licensed by the Department
9 of Labor to engage in nonconsensual towing shall be appointed by the
10 Governor and whose membership shall expire June 30, 2028;
11 8. One member from the commercial insurance industry shall be
12 appointed by the Speaker Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma State Senate
13 and whose membership shall expire June 30, 2029; and
14 9. One member from the Oklahoma Department of Transportation
15 shall be appointed by the Governor and whose membership shall expire
16 June 30, 2030.
17 Thereafter, persons appointed pursuant to paragraphs 1 through 9
18 of this subsection shall be appointed for terms of three (3) years
19 beginning July 1. Any vacancy shall be filled by the appointing
20 authority for the remainder of the unexpired term.
21 B. Members appointed pursuant to paragraphs 3 through 9 of
22 subsection A of this section shall remain engaged in the business or
23 industry described in subsection A of this section. Members so
24 appointed who no longer satisfy the requirements for his or her
Req. No. 16927 Page 8

1 Boar d position pursuant to subsection A of this section shall
2 provide notification of his or her change of status to his or her
3 appointing authority and to the chair of the Oklahoma Wrecker and
4 Towing Services Board and shall resign from the Board within thirty
5 (30) days of the date upon which the member no longer satisfies the
6 requirements of the appointment.
7 C. The members shall determine by majority vote of the quorum
8 of the Board who shall serve as chair. The chair shall be elected
9 annually, with the right to succeed himself or herself, from the
10 membership of the Board.
11 D. The Board shall meet at such times that the chair deems
12 necessary, but no meeting shall be held outside the State of
13 Oklahoma. All actions of the Board shall be by a quorum. Five
14 members of the Board shall constitute a quorum for the purpose of
15 transacting business. The Department of Labor shall provide
16 administrative support and a meeting venue for the Board.
17 E. Nothing in this act shall be construed to authorize the
18 Board to regulate consensual towing services, voluntary roadside
19 assistance, or privately negotiated towing contracts. The Board
20 shall promulgate rules under the authority of the Oklahoma
21 Department of Labor to carry out its intent and shall regulate the
22 wrecker and towing industry in this state, including:
23 1. Establishing reasonable tow rates for nonconsensual tows for
24 any rates not tied to the federal per diem rate. "Reasonable tow
Req. No. 16927 Page 9

1 rate s" means rates that are directly related to the actual cost of
2 providing the nonconsensual tow, include a modest and customary
3 margin, and do not exceed the maximum rates approved by the Board.
4 These rates may only be adjusted every three (3) years by the Board;
5 2. Establishing reasonable licensing, insurance, and equipment
6 requirements for any person engaging in towing and related services;
7 3. Establishing reasonable tow truck safety requirements for
8 any wrecker or wrecker vehicle as defined in Section 951 of Title 47
9 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
10 4. Establishing a procedure to accept and investigate
11 complaints from a consumer who claims that he or she has been
12 overcharged for fees related to nonconsensual towing, recovery, or
13 storage;
14 5. Determining and sanctioning excessive or unnecessary fees
15 charged to consumers related to nonconsensual towing, recovery, or
16 storage;
17 6. Requiring all entities permitted, licensed, or regulated by
18 the Board to provide all documents in response to information
19 requests by the Board pursuant to the investigation of consumer
20 complaints or Board complaints against the permittee or licensee;
21 7. Requiring all entities permitted, licensed, or regulated by
22 the Board to provide itemized billing for fees related to towing,
23 storage, or vehicle immobilization services that explains how the
24 charges were calculated;
Req. No. 16927 Page 10

